{
  "result": "At dusk, the city sounded like a giant typewriter. Buses hissed, crosswalk signals clicked, sneakers tapped punctuation across wet sidewalks, and somewhere above it all a train drew a long metallic line through the sky. I sat on a bench outside a corner bakery, holding a paper cup of coffee that had gone warm enough to forget, and watched windows light up one by one. Every window seemed to reveal a tiny universe: a person watering basil, two siblings arguing over a game controller, an elderly man ironing a shirt with ceremonial patience. None of them knew I existed, and still I felt threaded to them, stitched into the same evening.\n\nA child in a yellow raincoat stopped to inspect a puddle as if it were an ocean. She crouched, dropped a leaf, and cheered when it sailed beneath a streetlamp reflection. Her father called her name, half stern, half laughing, and she stood, triumphant, carrying that small victory like treasure. I realized then how often wonder survives in plain sight, disguised as ordinary weather and ordinary streets.\n\nBy the time I stood to leave, the bakery door opened and released a gust of warm air scented with cinnamon and yeast. For a brief second the whole block felt generous. I walked home slowly, listening to the city keep typing its endless, imperfect, beautiful story. Tomorrow it would revise itself with sirens, sunlight, and spilled conversations, but tonight it left me one clear line: pay attention, and life answers back.",
